article:
In geometry, a 'triangular prism' is a three-sided prism; it is a polyhedron
made of a triangular base, a translated copy, and 3 faces joining
corresponding sides.

Equivalently, it is a pentahedron of which two faces are parallel, while the
surface normals of the other three are in the same plane (which is not
necessarily parallel to the base planes). These three faces are parallelograms.
All cross-sections parallel to the base faces are the same triangle.
